entry.title: Acacia gunnii
entry.content: Pretty sure this is the first record of this species on the Vic. Volcanic Plains. Growing in typical habitat for this species; ie. dry, rocky site, lacking taller shrubs, relatively large distances between grass tussocks.

entry.title: Grevillea rosmarinifolia
entry.content: Foliage is quite flexible, with a slight sharpness to the tip. Growing on a cliff face / escarpment with fully grown Bursaria, Callitris and other fully grown plants. I mention fully grown because the attached (3 plants seen) was 50cm tall by 1m wide (possibly a bit less). Plants were very woody so probably old. There are no plants above the escarpment, which was Grey Box with wildflower understorey. There are no grevilleas recorded anywhere near here. It is a form of rosmarinifolia.

entry.title: Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa
entry.content: Locally rare on the plains part of Riddells Creek (common in forested areas nearby). Plains plants are pretty much restricted to Rail Reserve where there is only one population I am aware of.

entry.title: Leptorhynchos tenuifolius
entry.content: Continued moisture seems to allow this species to retain flowers over a very long period, maybe all year.

entry.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
entry.content: Single old female plant surrounded by many young plants, all female. No male in this copse. The 'fruit' pictured are actually galls, probably Cylindrococcus (Hemiptera).

entry.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
entry.content: Male plant. This species is now locally rare owing to habitat destruction. The few remaining plants appear to be restricted to rail reserves (grassy plains woodland). Possibly no longer a viable remnant population?

entry.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
entry.content: Keys out best as A.sp.3 but some features of fimbriatum too. fimbriatum because of purple anthers and appendages, unbranched stem, leaves not distantly ciliate (it has distant teeth). sp.3 features - erect fruiting pedicels, leaves present at flowering.
